@Article{	  bassi2016,
  abstract	= {A novel algorithm for self-consistent simulations of
		  long-range wakefield effects has been developed and applied
		  to the study of both longitudinal and transverse
		  coupled-bunch instabilities at NSLS-II. The algorithm is
		  implemented in the new parallel tracking code SPACE
		  (self-consistent parallel algorithm for collective effects)
		  discussed in the paper. The code is applicable for accurate
		  beam dynamics simulations in cases where both
		  bunch-to-bunch and intrabunch motions need to be taken into
		  account, such as chromatic head-tail effects on the
		  coupled-bunch instability of a beam with a nonuniform
		  filling pattern, or multibunch and single-bunch effects of
		  a passive higher-harmonic cavity. The numerical simulations
		  have been compared with analytical studies. For a beam with
		  an arbitrary filling pattern, intensity-dependent complex
		  frequency shifts have been derived starting from a system
